Prologue
"Please, oh king!" Queen Elaina pleaded, "Do not send her away! She is just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, while the royal advisor stood beside him. Thinking of this, the Ice King couldn't help but frown.
The baby girl looked like her mother: she had light blue eyes and snowy white hair, with a few strands of blue hair mixed in. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, up until then, he had only sons.
"You have only two choices, either kill this child or abandon her in the wilderness. Arvin, this is your punishment." He spat out her name viciously, as if it were poison. He always spoke this way.
The Frostland was not always a kingdom. It used to be divided into two parts, north and south. The northern part established a non-magic kingdom, while the southern part was a realm filled with magical power. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms engaged in endless warfare until the south proposed a ceasefire.
At that time, the south was already in despair, and royal members were willing to do anything to prevent this bloody conflict. They proposed marrying their only princess to the north to become the queen and give birth to a son as the future king. Afterwards, the south would merge with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Arvin thus married Prince Akul.
"Please, my king, for my child's safety, you can do anything to me, imprison me, exile me, even kill me." Queen Elaina pleaded, hugging the child tightly to her chest.
The Ice King lowered his head to look at the queen, his eyes filled with disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he might show her a shred of compassion. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, caring for him when he was at his lowest, and bearing him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the Ice King's words, the queen let out a sigh of relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Elaina both showed expressions of fear. She slowly lowered her head and looked at the floor. "As you wish, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Arvin's quarters. Afterward, he commanded the guards to bring Arvin to the execution ground where all the citizens could see.
When the guards escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens, seeing their only queen—also the kindest queen—about to be executed, felt extremely angry. Some cried, others shouted trying to attack the guards, and still others wanted to know why this was happening; but they all shared the same question.
"Release her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Arvin approached the stake, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for burning at the stake. Queen Elaina, the previous queen, would be burned alive. No one should be subjected to the fire penalty, not even criminals. In Frostland, burning at the stake was the cruelest punishment.
Elaina was bound to the stake, and the king began to narrate how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostland refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the stake, and a tear rolled down the face of the previous queen.
"Carly, survive!" Queen Elaina's life came to an end.
The hall was silent.
In the south wing of this cold palace, a ceaseless "tap tap" sound came from the room on the far left. Passersby servants were always curious about what was inside but too afraid to get close. Maids walked around the hall, whispering and spreading rumors. Some believed that the deceased Ice King's wife, Arvin, was living in this room, waiting to be released.
They were gravely mistaken. Avery thought as she walked toward the south wing, where servants walked back and forth along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are many rumors about TA, as TA is the only person allowed to enter the room.
Knocking on the door, Avery whispered, "Miss Carley, are you inside?" The complex door, adorned with snowflakes and crowns, which were symbols of the royal family, responded with a muffled silence.
TA didn't know if she would really let him in this time, unlike before. I still have bruises from last time. Avery recalled this and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carley threw a book at him, but apologized immediately when she realized who it was.
A soft voice echoed in the room, saying she couldn't go anywhere and must stay there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, unable to forget the consequences of barging in未经邀请地闯入上次的结果。
A soft voice echoed again in the room, seeming to say "Come in." Avery felt a chill, not sure if it was due to the cold or that voice. Despite having been there for many years, Avery still found it a bit strange to hear the voice coming from the room.
"She's coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. By normal standards, the sight inside the room was unusual, but that was to be expected. The room was filled with papers. Books lay scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were numerous ice sculptures. There were no windows, and very little light. It was also much colder here than in other parts of the palace (which spoke volumes). The room looked as though it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in disarray.
The girl in the room curled up in bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked as she sat by Carley's bed.
